Im back. I know I was desparately missed in my one week of absence, but no fear; Im here! This weeks Chopped data can be found here! I mostly constructed this on a plane so I didnt delve into anything too new or original. Really the only completely new thing this time around was the use of annotations and arrows, which is actually really helpful.

As always, the first step is to load packages and data.

library(ggplot2)
library(tidyverse)
library(viridis)

chopped <- read_tsv(
  "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2020/2020-08-25/chopped.tsv"
)

Now I want to remove all observations that are missing an IMDB rating. I also pivot the data longer to easily summarize ratings by judge and fix one clearly messed up judges name.

chopped <- chopped %>%
  filter(!is.na(episode_rating)) %>%
  pivot_longer(judge1:judge3,
               names_to = "judge_no",
               values_to = "judge") %>%
  mutate(judge = str_replace_all(judge, 
                                 "Aarn Sanchez",
                                 "Aarn Snchez"))

# Calculate average IMDB scores for individual judges
judge_ratings <- chopped %>% 
  group_by(judge) %>% 
  summarise(mean_rating = mean(episode_rating, na.rm = T),
            n_ep = n()) %>% 
  arrange(desc(mean_rating)) %>%
  rename("Number of\nepisodes" = n_ep)

Next, I need to calculate the weighted average of IMDB ratings across all judges.

wa <- sum(judge_ratings$mean_rating*judge_ratings$`Number of\nepisodes`)/
  sum(judge_ratings$`Number of\nepisodes`)

Finally, to make the plot. Its ordered from highest to lowest average IMBD rating, and the bars are colored by the number of episodes each judge participated in. Ive added a couple notations and arrows, which was new territory for me, but will be extremely useful for future plots.

ggplot(judge_ratings) + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = wa, 
             color = "white", 
             linetype = "dashed") + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = factor(judge, levels = rev(unique(judge)), ordered = T), 
               y = mean_rating, 
               fill = `Number of\nepisodes`), 
           stat = "identity", 
           width = 1) + 
  geom_curve(aes(x = judge[83], 
                 y = wa + .5, 
                 xend = judge[83], 
                 yend = wa + .05), 
             color = "white",
             curvature = -.2, 
             arrow = arrow(angle = 45, 
                           length = unit(3, units = "mm"))) + 
  geom_curve(aes(x = judge[13], 
                 y = wa + .8, 
                 xend = judge[10], 
                 yend = wa + .5), 
             color = "white",
             curvature = .4, 
             arrow = arrow(angle = 45, 
                           length = unit(3, units = "mm"))) +
  annotate("text", 
           label = "Average IMDB rating\nfor all judges (8.38)", 
           color = "white",
           fontface = "bold",
           x = judge_ratings$judge[80], 
           wa + .8) + 
  annotate("text", 
           label = "A bunch of\none-hit wonders!", 
           color = "white", 
           fontface = "bold",
           x = judge_ratings$judge[15], 
           wa + .9) +
  scale_fill_viridis(option = "E", 
                     direction = 1) + 
  coord_flip() + 
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank(), 
        plot.background = element_rect(color = "#44475a", 
                                       fill = "#44475a"), 
        panel.background = element_rect(color = "#44475a", 
                                        fill = "#44475a"), 
        legend.background = element_rect(color = "#44475a", 
                                         fill = "#44475a"), 
        legend.text = element_text(color = "white",
                                   face = "bold"), 
        legend.title = element_text(color = "white",
                                    face = "bold"), 
        axis.text = element_text(color = "white",
                                 size = 8),
        axis.title = element_text(color = "white",
                                  face = "bold"),
        plot.title = element_text(color = "white",
                                  hjust = 0.5,
                                  face = "bold")) +
  labs(title = "Average IMDB Ratings for Judges",
       y = "IMDB Rating",
       x = "")

As always, the image looks like poop in R Markdown. When running the code in RStudio you can expand the plot window to full screen and it looks great. With that unimpressive outro, weve concluded this weeks exploration.
